<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1437,582,1604]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1505,1530]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[348,540,1505,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nyx">
<emphasis box="[348,540,1505,1530]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Allometopon nyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is best characterized by one pair of large, light brown, subrectangular scutal stripes that nearly touch and reach the transverse suture, and barely meet the posterior margin. The pleuron, legs and most of the head are also bright white and the surstylus is very small and triangular.
</paragraph>
